In [ ]:
connection = engine.connect()
cursor_cab = connection.execute('SELECT * FROM Cab_Driver')
cab_driver_df = pd.DataFrame(data = cursor_cab.fetchall(), columns= cursor_cab.keys())

cursor_safe = connection.execute('SELECT * FROM Safety_Labels')
safety_labels_df = pd.DataFrame(data = cursor_safe.fetchall(), columns= cursor_safe.keys())

cursor_sens = connection.execute('SELECT * FROM Sensor_Data')
sensor_data_df = pd.DataFrame(data = cursor_sens.fetchall(), columns= cursor_sens.keys())
connection.close()

Check for extreme values first¶

In [ ]:
# Get all extreme values from sensor_safety_df

def calc_gates(series, gate_scale=1.5):
    Q1 = series.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = series.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - (gate_scale * IQR)
    upper_bound = Q3 + (gate_scale * IQR)
    return lower_bound, upper_bound

def get_extreme_values(df, column):
    lower_bound, upper_bound = calc_gates(df[column])
    return df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)]

for col in sensor_safety_df.columns:
    if sensor_safety_df[col].dtype != 'object':
        if len(get_extreme_values(sensor_safety_df, col)>0):
            print(f"Extreme values for {col}")
            display(get_extreme_values(sensor_safety_df, col).sort_values(by=col, ascending=False))
            print(f"25% of {col}")
            display(sensor_safety_df[col].quantile(0.25))
            print(f"75% of {col}")
            display(sensor_safety_df[col].quantile(0.75))
        else:
            print(f"No extreme values found for {col}")
        print('\n')

Feature Engineering¶

  • Engineer more features for data analysis.

Acceleration Magnitude¶

  • Measure of the absolute change in speed or force, regardless of direction of the movement. $$ \sqrt{\text{acc\_x}^2 + \text{acc\_y}^2 + \text{acc\_z}^2 } $$
In [ ]:
# Calculate magnitude of acceleration
acc_mag = ((sensor_safety_df['acceleration_x']**2 + sensor_safety_df['acceleration_y']**2 + sensor_safety_df['acceleration_z']**2)**0.5).sort_values(ascending=False)

# Plot histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

sns.histplot(acc_mag, bins=100, kde=True, color='red', alpha=0.5)

plt.xlabel('Acceleration', fontsize=14, fontfamily='serif')
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14, fontfamily='serif')

plt.title('Distribution of Acceleration (m/s^2)', fontsize=20, fontfamily='serif', fontweight='bold')

plt.show()

We removed magnitude acceleration values of $70{m/s^2}$ as it is impossible for normal vehicles like taxis to ever exceed this value (around 210km/h per unit second!)

In [ ]:
sensor_safety_df['acceleration_magnitude'] = acc_mag[acc_mag < 70]

Gyro Magnitude¶

  • Rate of directional change between successive orientations meaurements in rad/s $$ \sqrt{\text{gyro\_x}^2 + \text{gyro\_y}^2 + \text{gyro\_z}^2 } $$
In [ ]:
# Calculate magnitude of gyro
gyro_mag = ((sensor_safety_df['gyro_x']**2 + sensor_safety_df['gyro_y']**2 + sensor_safety_df['gyro_z']**2)**0.5).sort_values(ascending=False)

# Plot histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

sns.histplot(gyro_mag, bins=100, kde=True, color='red', alpha=0.5)

plt.xlabel('Gyro', fontsize=14, fontfamily='serif')
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14, fontfamily='serif')

plt.title('Distribution of Gyro (rad/s)', fontsize=20, fontfamily='serif', fontweight='bold')

plt.show()

A gyroscope reading of 70 radians per second is extremely high and would be beyond the typical range of gyroscope readings for automotive applications. The values of 70 radians per second would correspond to a very high and unrealistic rate of rotation

In [ ]:
sensor_safety_df['gyro_magnitude'] = gyro_mag[gyro_mag < 70]

Age of Drivers¶

  • Current age of the driver
  • Calculated using date of birth $$ \text{Age} = \text{Current Year} - \text{Date of Birth} $$
In [ ]:
#Convert the data type of 'date_of_birth' to datetime
cab_driver_df['date_of_birth'] = pd.to_datetime(cab_driver_df['date_of_birth'])

# Find age of drivers
cab_driver_df['date_of_birth'] = pd.to_datetime(cab_driver_df['date_of_birth'])
cur_year = pd.to_datetime('today').year
cab_driver_df['driver_age'] = cur_year - cab_driver_df['date_of_birth'].dt.year

Pitch¶

  • Rotation about the transverse axis (side-to-side tilt)
  • Measured in radians
  • Calculated by: $$ \theta = tan^{-1}\left(\frac{acc_{y}}{\sqrt{{acc_{x}}^{2} + {acc_{z}}^{2}}}\right) $$

Duration¶

  • Total duration of a trip
  • Calculated by taking $\max (seconds) $ grouped by booking ID
  • Assumes that each trip starts from 0 seconds (since trips cannot just start halfway)

Chi-Square Contingency Test¶

  • A deeper dive into the respective bins of driver ratings, split into different bins
  • Use of chi-square to find out how driver ratings was being given based on drivers' ratings
In [ ]:
df_eda = cab_driver_df.copy()

rating_categories = pd.cut(df_eda['driver_rating'], bins=[0, 2, 3, 4, 5], include_lowest=True, 
                           labels=['Low', 'Below Average', 'Above Average', 'High'])

# Create a new column 'rating_categories' based on the driver_rating
df_eda['rating_categories'] = rating_categories

# Cross tabulation
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df_eda['gender'], df_eda['rating_categories'])

# Perform the chi-square test
chi2, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

# Plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(contingency_table, annot=True,fmt='d', cmap='crest_r')
plt.title('Heatmap of Driver Rating by Gender')
plt.xlabel('Rating Categories')
plt.ylabel('Gender')

plt.show()

# Output the results of chi-square test
chi2_sq_results = {
    'Chi-Square Statistic': chi2,
    'P-Value': p_value,
    'Degrees of Freedom': dof,
    'Expected Frequencies': expected
}

chi2_sq_results
Out[ ]:
{'Chi-Square Statistic': 8.862626887082175,
 'P-Value': 0.03117420853879594,
 'Degrees of Freedom': 3,
 'Expected Frequencies': array([[ 4.9 , 76.44, 81.83, 81.83],
        [ 5.1 , 79.56, 85.17, 85.17]])}

Observations

  • We can see that there are a very small amount of drivers who have low ratings.
  • We can also see that there are greater number of female drivers with above average driver ratings (3<=x<4) but greater number of male drivers with below average (2<=x<3) and high driver ratings (4<=x).
  • Previously, it is seen that on average it was equal because the male with high ratings balance out the below average ratings to match the amount of above average ratings that the females have received.
  • Test results indicate that there is a statistically significant association between gender and driver rating categories, as p-value of 0.03 is less than the p-value bench mark of 0.05, suggesting that driver ratings may be influenced by gender.

Clustering¶

  • A type of unsupervised machine learning method that involves grouping similar data points together.
  • Identify inherent structures or patterns within a dataset without the need of labeled outcomes.
  • K-Means Clustering is used:
    • Aims to partition a set of data points into meaningful subgroups or clusters based on their similarities
    • Each data point belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean
In [ ]:
driver_numerical = ['num_of_years_driving_exp', 'driver_rating', 'driver_age']
X = cab_driver_df[driver_numerical]

# Standardize the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Using the optimal number of clusters from the elbow method
wcss = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init='k-means++', random_state=42, n_init=10, max_iter=300)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot the elbow method graph
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss, marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.title("Elbow Method For Optimal K")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("WCSS")
plt.show()

Observations

  • Even though elbow plot does not reveal how many clusters is the optimal number to use, 4 would be the most logical number to draw conclusions from.

Clusters Interpretation¶

  • Cluster 0 - Less Experienced and Average-Aged Drivers with Lower Ratings
    • Drivers in this cluster appear to be less experienced and have an average age within the dataset range.
    • Lower driver rating suggests a potential need for improvement or may be influenced by various factors affecting their performance.
  • Cluster 1 - Less Experienced and Older Drivers with High Rating
    • Drivers with fewer years of experience but older
    • Despite their lower experience, they have received positive feedback, indicating a high level of proficiency.
  • Cluster 2 - Experienced and Younger Drivers with Average Ratings
    • Seems to represent a group of drivers who have accumulated significant driving experience at a relatively young age.
    • Despite being younger, their average driver rating suggest a reasonable level of competence.
  • Cluster 3 - Experienced and Older Drivers with Average Ratings
    • Consists of seasoned drivers who have been driving for a long time and are relatively older.
    • Similar to Cluster 0, the drivers in this cluster have an average driver rating, indicating a consistent performance.

Anomaly Detection¶

  • IsolationForest is used for anomaly detection and is effective for identifying outliers or anomalies in the dataset.
  • IsolationForest:
    • Identify patterns or instances that deviate significantly from expected behaviour of the dataset.
    • Isolates anomalies by recursively partitioning the data into subsets
    • Randomly selects a feature and a split value for each partitioning
    • Anomalies are expected to have shorter paths in the resulting trees, usually isolated with fewer splits.
    • Performs well in high-dimensional space

from bokeh.io import output_notebook, show
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, FactorRange
from bokeh.plotting import figure
from bokeh.transform import factor_cmap
from bokeh.palettes import MediumContrast3

output_notebook()

# Create a grouped bar chart using FactorRange
# Group by gender then each group by driver_rating_binned

genders = list(df_eda['gender'].unique())
driver_ratings = list(df_eda['driver_rating_binned'].cat.categories)

freq = df_eda.groupby(['gender', 'driver_rating_binned']).aggregate({'driver_rating_binned': 'count'})
freq = freq.rename({'driver_rating_binned': 'count'}, axis=1).reset_index()

data = {bin : list(freq['count'][freq['driver_rating_binned'] == bin].values) for bin in driver_ratings}

# Add gender to the dictionary
data['gender'] = genders

x = [(gender, driver_rating) for gender in genders for driver_rating in driver_ratings]
counts = sum(zip(data['2-3'], data['3-4'], data['4-5']), ())

source = ColumnDataSource(data=dict(x=x, counts=counts))

p = figure(x_range=FactorRange(*x), height=350, width=750, title="Count of Driving Rating", toolbar_location=None, tools="", output_backend="svg", x_axis_label="Gender", y_axis_label="Count")
p.title.text_font_size = '20pt'

p.vbar(x='x', top='counts', width=0.9, source=source, line_color="white", fill_color=factor_cmap('x', palette=MediumContrast3, factors=driver_ratings, start=1, end=2))

p.y_range.start = 0
p.x_range.range_padding = 0.1
p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1
p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None

show(p)
